## What I built

A plain-PHP (no framework, zero runtime dependencies) image gallery on SQLite + GD, served by PHP's built-in web server.

**Flow:** Register/sign in → upload an image with a caption → it appears on the public gallery as a thumbnail → clicking it opens the full image + caption. Owners can delete their own images.

**Routes** (`public/index.php`): `/`, `/register`, `/login`, `/logout`, `/upload`, `/delete`, `/view/{id}`, `/image/{id}` (full bytes), `/thumb/{id}` (thumbnail bytes).

## Run it on port 5037

```bash
cp .env.example .env          # optional; defaults work
php -S 127.0.0.1:5037 -t public public/router.php
```

Then open http://127.0.0.1:5037. The DB and upload dir are created on first run. To syntax-check first: `php -l public/index.php` (repeat per file).

## How each security requirement is met

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | PDO prepared statements with bound params everywhere (`controllers.php`, `helpers.php`) |
| Password hashing | `password_hash(PASSWORD_DEFAULT)` (bcrypt, salted) + `password_verify`; dummy-hash verify for unknown users to flatten timing |
| XSS | Single `e()` (`htmlspecialchars`, `ENT_QUOTES`) on all output + strict CSP with no inline JS |
| CSRF | Per-session token required on **every** POST, compared with `hash_equals` (`require_csrf`) |
| Access control / IDOR | Delete is owner-scoped (`WHERE id AND user_id`) with an explicit ownership check before acting |
| Secure cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` under HTTPS (or `FORCE_SECURE_COOKIE`); session id regenerated on start + login |
| Security headers | CSP, `nosniff`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`, CORP, HSTS |
| No error leakage | `display_errors` off; uncaught errors logged, generic 500 shown (`bootstrap.php`) |
| No hardcoded secrets | All config via env / `.env` |

**Upload hardening:** content-based allow-list (`finfo` + `getimagesize`, ignoring client filename/Content-Type) limited to JPEG/PNG/GIF/WebP; `MAX_UPLOAD_BYTES` (5 MB default); random server-generated names (`bin2hex(random_bytes(16))`); stored in `storage/uploads/` **outside** the web root (the dev router refuses to serve it and blocks all `.php` execution there), written `0644` and streamed back with a fixed allow-listed `Content-Type` + `nosniff`; path-traversal containment via filename pattern + `realpath()` confinement check (`safe_upload_path`).

Manifest is `composer.json` (declares PHP ≥ 8.1 and the `pdo_sqlite`/`gd`/`fileinfo`/`session` extensions; no third-party packages, so `composer install` is optional). `README.md` covers setup, the port-5037 command, config, and the `php.ini` upload-size caveat.

One design note worth flagging: I dropped the `APP_SECRET` placeholder from `.env.example` because nothing in the app actually consumed it — leaving an unused "secret" in the manifest would have been misleading. PHP's session layer already provides cryptographically secure session IDs, and the CSRF token is per-session random.
